## Additional notes on transformations (st_transform)

So far, we’ve let each dataset live in its native coordinate reference system (CRS):

- The crime points use WGS84 (EPSG 4326), i.e. longitude/latitude in degrees.
- The LSOA shapefile uses British National Grid (EPSG 27700), i.e. eastings/northings in metres.

When we only map each layer separately or join by ID columns (like LSOA code), different CRSs are fine. 

The CRS becomes crucial when we:

- Overlay layers in the same map (e.g. crime points on LSOA polygons).
- Do spatial operations that depend on geometry (e.g. point‑in‑polygon joins, buffers, distances, spatial weights, spatial clustering).

In those cases, all layers must share the same CRS, and that’s where st_transform() comes in: it reprojects one layer into the CRS of another.

Checking the CRS

```{r}
st_crs(sf)          # crime points (WGS84, EPSG:4326)
st_crs(surrey_lsoa) # LSOA polygons (often BNG, EPSG:27700)

```

You want these to match before doing geometry‑based work.

Reprojecting with st_transform()
To transform the crime points into British National Grid (so they match the LSOA polygons):

```{r}
sf_bng <- st_transform(sf, crs = 27700)
st_crs(sf_bng)
```

Now sf_bng and surrey_lsoa share the same CRS, so you can safely do things like:


```{r}
crimes_per_lsoa_geom <- st_join(sf_bng, surrey_lsoa, join = st_within) |>
  count(lsoa21cd, name = "n_crimes")
```


“st_as_sf() turns our table into spatial data by creating a geometry column and assigning a CRS.
st_transform() doesn’t change the data itself; it just re-expresses the geometry in another CRS so different spatial layers can line up and we can safely do geometric operations.”





